\begin{frame}{The difference of two dice}
\begin{columns}[T]

  \begin{column}{.6\textwidth}
    We roll two dice and define the random variable $x$ as the absolute value of the difference between them.
    Each group is assigned a value of $x$, and is to count the number of ways of obtaining that value of $x$.
    For example, rolling 3 and 5 is one way to get $x=2$, and rolling 5 and 3 is another.

    \begin{tabular}{ll}
      \emph{group} & $x$ \\
      A & 0 \\
      B & 1 \\
      C & 2 \\
      D & 3 \\
      E & 4 \\
      F & 5 
    \end{tabular}
  \end{column}

  \begin{column}{.4\textwidth}
    \noindent\includegraphics[width=3in]{ch10/figs/dice}
  \end{column}
\end{columns}

\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{The difference of two dice}
\begin{columns}[T]

  \begin{column}{.6\textwidth}
